20
00:01:30,000 --> 00:01:35,000
What happened when the young Jeff Bezos' car accidentally rolled downhill?

21
00:01:35,000 --> 00:01:38,000
Was it A? Jeff jumped in and pulled the handbrake?

22
00:01:38,000 --> 00:01:41,000
B? Jeff's granddad lost the thumb?

23
00:01:41,000 --> 00:01:44,000
Or C? Jeff's hair fell out.

24
00:01:44,000 --> 00:01:49,000
Well, Jeff Bezos is bored so maybe it's C? His hair fell out.

25
00:01:49,000 --> 00:01:51,000
Okay Georgina, we'll find out later.

26
00:01:51,000 --> 00:01:55,000
As a company Amazon has been remarkably strong.

27
00:01:55,000 --> 00:02:01,000
It survived the dot-com crash of 2000 and saw profits jump during the COVID pandemic.

28
00:02:01,000 --> 00:02:04,000
As more and more people started shopping online.

29
00:02:04,000 --> 00:02:10,000
Retail analyst Natalie Berg thinks Amazon's success is due to its customer strategy.

30
00:02:10,000 --> 00:02:15,000
As she explains to BBC Radio 4 program seriously.

31
00:02:15,000 --> 00:02:21,000
Jeff Bezos applied this concept to Amazon by relentlessly focusing on customers,

32
00:02:21,000 --> 00:02:26,000
by putting them at the heart of the business, that that would attract more customers,

33
00:02:26,000 --> 00:02:31,000
more traffic to its site, which would in turn attract more sellers,

34
00:02:31,000 --> 00:02:34,000
which would mean a greater selection for customers,

35
00:02:34,000 --> 00:02:37,000
which again would enhance the customer experience.

36
00:02:38,000 --> 00:02:42,000
Natalie thinks that Amazon put customers at the heart of their business.

37
00:02:42,000 --> 00:02:46,000
In other words, they make customers the most important part.

38
00:02:46,000 --> 00:02:49,000
This improves Amazon's customer experience,

39
00:02:49,000 --> 00:02:53,000
a customer's total perception of their experience with a business,

40
00:02:53,000 --> 00:02:56,000
including such things as the quality of service

41
00:02:56,000 --> 00:02:58,000
and support if something goes wrong.

42
00:02:58,000 --> 00:03:01,000
Customers can write reviews on Amazon's website,

43
00:03:01,000 --> 00:03:04,000
and happy customers means more web traffic,

44
00:03:04,000 --> 00:03:07,000
the number of people visiting a particular website.

45
00:03:07,000 --> 00:03:10,000
In the difficult years following the dot-com crash,

46
00:03:10,000 --> 00:03:12,000
Jeff Bezos started Marketplace,

47
00:03:12,000 --> 00:03:16,000
where other sellers compete with Amazon's own products.

48
00:03:16,000 --> 00:03:18,000
More sellers brought more customers,

49
00:03:18,000 --> 00:03:20,000
which in turn brought down prices.

50
00:03:20,000 --> 00:03:24,000
Then in 2013, Bezos bought the Washington Post.

51
00:03:24,000 --> 00:03:28,000
And in 2019, he launched his space exploration company Blue Origin

52
00:03:28,000 --> 00:03:31,000
to explore mineral resources on Mars.

53
00:03:31,000 --> 00:03:35,000
Most recently, Jeff Bezos has set his sights on even bigger things,

54
00:03:35,000 --> 00:03:38,000
saving the future of the planet.

55
00:03:38,000 --> 00:03:43,000
Bezos chose Tom Rivet-Karnack of the Environmental Group Global Optimism

56
00:03:43,000 --> 00:03:48,000
to help Amazon meet climate initiative goals aimed at slowing climate change.

57
00:03:48,000 --> 00:03:51,000
Here is Tom Rivet-Karnack, telling David Baker,

58
00:03:51,000 --> 00:03:54,000
presenter of BBC Radio 4s seriously,

59
00:03:54,000 --> 00:03:58,000
about his conversation with Jeff Bezos.

60
00:03:58,000 --> 00:04:01,000
It did seem to me that it was a legacy issue for him

61
00:04:01,000 --> 00:04:03,000
that he wanted to be on the right side of history.

62
00:04:03,000 --> 00:04:06,000
And you don't think it's just greenwashing in the end.

63
00:04:06,000 --> 00:04:08,000
How do you define that?

64
00:04:08,000 --> 00:04:11,000
I mean, would you define greenwashing if you said somebody got into this issue

65
00:04:11,000 --> 00:04:15,000
because they wanted to improve a reputation of a company or an individual?

66
00:04:15,000 --> 00:04:17,000
Actually, that's fine, right?

67
00:04:17,000 --> 00:04:21,000
As long as they do something meaningful and deliver a major outcome.

68
00:04:21,000 --> 00:04:25,000
Protecting the planet is what Jeff Bezos wants to be part of his legacy,

69
00:04:25,000 --> 00:04:28,000
the achievements of his life that will continue after he dies.

70
00:04:28,000 --> 00:04:33,000
In other words, Bezos wants to be on the right side of history,

71
00:04:33,000 --> 00:04:37,000
judged to have acted correctly or morally by future generations.

72
00:04:37,000 --> 00:04:41,000
Ultimately though, it's real action on climate change that counts,

73
00:04:41,000 --> 00:04:43,000
not just greenwashing.

74
00:04:43,000 --> 00:04:45,000
Do you know this new expression, Georgina?

75
00:04:45,000 --> 00:04:50,000
Well, I know that whitewashing means trying to hide the truth about something.

76
00:04:50,000 --> 00:04:53,000
Right, so greenwashing means trying to make people believe

77
00:04:53,000 --> 00:04:57,000
that your company is doing more to protect the environment than it really is.

78
00:04:57,000 --> 00:05:00,000
Well, with so many achievements already behind him,

79
00:05:00,000 --> 00:05:03,000
I'm sure Jeff has made his grandparents very proud,

80
00:05:03,000 --> 00:05:06,000
which reminds me of your quiz question, Neil.

81
00:05:06,000 --> 00:05:10,000
Ah, yes, I asked Georgina what happened when the car Jeff Bezos

82
00:05:10,000 --> 00:05:15,000
and his granddad Lawrence were fixing accidentally rolled downhill.

83
00:05:15,000 --> 00:05:18,000
I thought it was C, that Jeff lost all his hair.

84
